SIMPLE: infidelity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infidelity
<hw>In`fi*del"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Infidelities</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>infidelitas</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>infid⟦eacute⟧lit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Lack of faith or belief in some religious system;
especially, a lack of faith in, or disbelief of, the inspiration of the
Scriptures, of the divine origin of Christianity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is, indeed, no doubt but that vanity is one of the principal
causes of <qex>infidelity</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>V. Knox.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unfaithfulness to the marriage vow or contract;
violation of the marriage covenant by adultery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Breach of trust; unfaithfulness to a charge, or to
moral obligation; treachery; deceit; <as>as, the <ex>infidelity</ex> of
a servant</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>infidelity</xex> of
friends.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W. Temple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infield</ent>⟦br⟧
